		<title>09LIFE ON THE FARM</title>
		<content> My mother usually wakes at 6.OO in the
 morning to check the stock but I get  
 up at 7.3O to feed the rabbits and see
 my pony.  When I return home from     
 school on Mondays I catch 7 horses for
 the Riding for the Disabled children  
 who live locally.  My mother also     
 teaches disabled adults to drive a    
 pony and trap.  The trap is specially 
 adapted to take a wheelchair safely.  
 Working in a farm is hard but very    
 rewarding, especially at calving or   
 foaling time.                         
                                       
                                       
                                       
                                       
                                       
                                       
                                       
                                       
